  "summaries": [
    {
      "id": 871247,
      "category": "team",
      "content": "Jitsi Meet's Prosody and Jigasi components contained a SIP header injection vulnerability in the interaction between `mod_filter_iq_rayo.lua` and the call handling backend. The Prosody filter implemented an incomplete blocklist that stripped only three specific internal header names (`X-outbound-call-initiator-user`, `X-outbound-call-initiator-group`, and `JvbRoomName` on visitor nodes) from client-supplied Rayo `<dial>` IQ stanzas, but forwarded all other arbitrary headers unfiltered to Jigasi. Jigasi's `CallControl.java` consumed these headers without validation and stored them in an `extraHeaders` map. `SipGatewaySession.java` then injected every entry directly into outbound SIP `INVITE` requests as raw protocol-level headers. This allowed authenticated users with outbound-call privileges to inject arbitrary SIP headers such as `P-Asserted-Identity` and `Remote-Party-ID`, enabling Caller ID spoofing on outgoing SIP calls in environments where Jigasi operates as a trusted SIP peer.\n\nChanges:\n* fix(security): Implement whitelist for Rayo dial headers\n  * https://github.com/jitsi/jitsi-meet/pull/17480\n\nWe thank @pmgjoe for submitting this report to us.",
